STEP 1 — Launch EC2 Instances

Go to AWS Console

Then open:

Amazon EC2
Create First Instance (EFS-1)
1. Click “Launch Instance”
2. Configure Instance

Fill:

Setting	Value
Name	EFS-1
AMI	Amazon Linux
Instance Type	t2.micro
Key Pair	Create/select key pair
Network	Default VPC
Subnet	Subnet-1a
Security Group	Create new
3. Configure Security Group

Add these inbound rules:

Type	Port	Source
SSH	22	Anywhere
NFS	2049	Anywhere
Why?
SSH → allows terminal access
NFS → required for EFS mounting
4. Launch Instance

Click:

Launch Instance
Create Second Instance

Repeat same process.

Only change:

Setting	Value
Name	EFS-2
Subnet	Subnet-1b
STEP 2 — Create Amazon EFS

Open:

Amazon EFS
1. Click “Create File System”
2. Configure EFS
Setting	Value
Name	Optional
VPC	Default
Regional	Enabled
Why Regional?

Regional EFS works across multiple AZs.

3. Network Settings

You will see mount targets.

Important:

Remove default security groups.

Attach:

The same security group used by EC2
Why?

The EC2 instances and EFS must allow NFS traffic between them.

4. Create File System

Click:

Create File System

Wait until:

Status becomes Available
STEP 3 — Connect to EC2 Using PowerShell
Open PowerShell

On Windows:

Open 2 PowerShell windows

One for:

EFS-1
EFS-2
Find Public IP

In EC2 dashboard:

Select instance
Copy Public IPv4 address
SSH into EFS-1

Example:

ssh -i "efs.pem" ec2-user@54.xx.xx.xx
Explanation
Part	Meaning
ssh	remote login
-i	identity key
efs.pem	private key
ec2-user	Linux username
IP	EC2 public IP
Fix Permission Error (If Any)

If Windows says:

bad permissions

Run:

icacls efs.pem /inheritance:r
icacls efs.pem /grant:r "%username%:R"

Then retry SSH.

Switch to Root User

Run:

sudo su
Why?

Administrative privileges needed.

Create Directory

Run:

mkdir efs

Check:

ls

You should see:

efs
Install Amazon EFS Utilities

Run:

yum install -y amazon-efs-utils
Why?

This package contains:

EFS mount helper
TLS support
NFS utilities
Verify Installation

Run:

rpm -qa | grep efs

OR:

mount.efs --version
Repeat Same Steps on EFS-2

Do:

SSH
sudo su
mkdir efs
install amazon-efs-utils
STEP 4 — Attach EFS to EC2
Get Mount Command

Go to:

EFS console
Select file system
Click Attach

Choose:

Mount via DNS

You will see command like:

sudo mount -t efs fs-12345678:/ efs
Run Command on BOTH EC2 Instances

Example:

mount -t efs fs-12345678:/ efs
Verify Mount

Run:

df -h

You should see EFS mounted.

Example:

fs-12345678:/   8.0E   0   8.0E   0%   /root/efs
STEP 5 — Test Shared Storage
On EFS-1

Go inside directory:

cd efs

Create file:

touch hello.txt

Check:

ls
On EFS-2

Run:

cd efs
ls

You should immediately see:

hello.txt
